00:54:31.060 --> 00:54:33.793
Oh.

00:54:33.793 --> 00:54:35.198
[BLOWS RASPBERRY] OK.

00:54:35.198 --> 00:54:36.870
[LAUGHTER]

00:54:36.870 --> 00:54:40.067
Well, now that you all know
about-- what did I say?

00:54:40.067 --> 00:54:41.650
That was only like
100 people, though.

00:54:41.650 --> 00:54:42.520
OK.

00:54:42.520 --> 00:54:45.770
OK, for those of you who
didn't-- Dutch Hunger Winter,

00:54:45.770 --> 00:54:47.720
here's the deal.

00:54:47.720 --> 00:54:52.660
If you were a fetus in Holland
during the winter of 1944,

00:54:52.660 --> 00:54:54.870
something very interesting
happened with you.

00:54:54.870 --> 00:54:58.130
1944, Holland is still
occupied by the Nazis.

00:54:58.130 --> 00:55:00.420
Nazis are being
pressured on all fronts.

00:55:00.420 --> 00:55:03.360
In the process of losing,
they're falling back.

00:55:03.360 --> 00:55:05.980
They're losing a lot of
the land they've occupied.

00:55:05.980 --> 00:55:08.080
And what they decide
to do that winter

00:55:08.080 --> 00:55:11.070
is, because they need some
food and because they wanted

00:55:11.070 --> 00:55:14.000
to punish the Dutch for
beginning to be more openly

00:55:14.000 --> 00:55:16.290
in the resistance, what
they did was, that winter,

00:55:16.290 --> 00:55:19.990
they diverted all of the
food in Holland to Germany.

00:55:19.990 --> 00:55:23.320
And historically known as
the Dutch Hunger Winter.

00:55:23.320 --> 00:55:27.080
Essentially, people went
from a perfectly fine,

00:55:27.080 --> 00:55:29.940
healthy-- amid the
context of a war--

00:55:29.940 --> 00:55:32.520
Western-European diet,
down to something

00:55:32.520 --> 00:55:34.520
like that from out of nowhere.

00:55:34.520 --> 00:55:38.290
40,000 people starved to death
during the Dutch Hunger Winter.

00:55:38.290 --> 00:55:40.950
Something very
interesting occurred,

00:55:40.950 --> 00:55:45.070
if you were a third-trimester
fetus, during the Dutch Hunger

00:55:45.070 --> 00:55:47.680
Winter, because it only
lasted for the winter.

00:55:47.680 --> 00:55:51.020
The Allies came in,
liberated Holland after that.

00:55:51.020 --> 00:55:53.520
And it went to something
like this, something

00:55:53.520 --> 00:55:56.340
resembling a step
function of starvation

00:55:56.340 --> 00:55:58.440
for about three months.

00:55:58.440 --> 00:56:01.940
If you were third-trimester
fetus during the Dutch Hunger

00:56:01.940 --> 00:56:05.790
Winter, your body learned
something important,

00:56:05.790 --> 00:56:09.380
which is here is not a whole
lot of calories out there.

00:56:09.380 --> 00:56:12.840
During third trimester,
fetuses are in some way--

00:56:12.840 --> 00:56:17.620
and this is metaphorical--
deciding, learning how much,

00:56:17.620 --> 00:56:19.450
in the way of
nutrients out there

00:56:19.450 --> 00:56:22.440
in the world, how readily
do calories come in?

00:56:22.440 --> 00:56:24.220
How is the fetus finding out?

00:56:24.220 --> 00:56:26.350
By way of mom's circulation.

00:56:26.350 --> 00:56:27.720
Mom is starving.

00:56:27.720 --> 00:56:30.850
And thus, much lower levels of
nutrients in the bloodstream.

00:56:30.850 --> 00:56:33.720
And the fetus, at that
point in development,

00:56:33.720 --> 00:56:36.170
is saying, metaphorically,
well, what's

00:56:36.170 --> 00:56:38.220
it like out there in
this place I'm going

00:56:38.220 --> 00:56:39.890
to be heading to rather soon?

00:56:39.890 --> 00:56:42.490
What's the nutritional
profile like?

00:56:42.490 --> 00:56:45.760
There's not much in the
way of food out there.

00:56:45.760 --> 00:56:49.760
And as a result, the fetus
has-- and the term used now

00:56:49.760 --> 00:56:52.110
is "metabolic programming."

00:56:52.110 --> 00:56:56.380
There is metabolic programming,
or metabolic imprinting--

00:56:56.380 --> 00:56:58.110
notice the word
"imprinting" here being

00:56:58.110 --> 00:56:59.960
used in a completely
different sense

00:56:59.960 --> 00:57:03.250
than we've heard about
already-- metabolic programming

00:57:03.250 --> 00:57:07.950
to produce what is called
a thrifty phenotype.

00:57:07.950 --> 00:57:11.030
The fetus, realizing
there is nothing out there

00:57:11.030 --> 00:57:13.440
in the way of plentiful
food, what it does

00:57:13.440 --> 00:57:16.810
is it programs its
pancreas to function in

00:57:16.810 --> 00:57:18.810
a certain way forever after.

00:57:18.810 --> 00:57:20.500
What does the pancreas do?

00:57:20.500 --> 00:57:24.010
The smallest smidgen of
food hits the bloodstream,

00:57:24.010 --> 00:57:26.690
and the pancreas is
pumping out insulin,

00:57:26.690 --> 00:57:29.970
which helps store all that
stuff and quickly scarf up

00:57:29.970 --> 00:57:32.250
every bit of nutrient
in the bloodstream

00:57:32.250 --> 00:57:34.150
and store it away,
because you've got

00:57:34.150 --> 00:57:36.440
to be as efficient as possible.

00:57:36.440 --> 00:57:39.930
And you've metabolically
programmed your kidneys,

00:57:39.930 --> 00:57:42.960
so that your kidneys are
incredibly good at retaining

00:57:42.960 --> 00:57:45.060
salt. Because along
with starvation,

00:57:45.060 --> 00:57:46.710
there's going to
be salt shortages.

00:57:46.710 --> 00:57:49.780
So really hold on to salt.
And you are born with a body

00:57:49.780 --> 00:57:54.770
with a thrifty metabolism,
very good at retaining salt,

00:57:54.770 --> 00:57:58.590
and spectacular at storing
away every bit of nutrients

00:57:58.590 --> 00:58:00.560
that hits the bloodstream.

00:58:00.560 --> 00:58:04.450
So at that point, you go
back to this sort of diet.

00:58:04.450 --> 00:58:06.320
And you have that for
the rest of your life.

00:58:06.320 --> 00:58:09.270
And what has now been shown
with the Dutch Hunger Winter

00:58:09.270 --> 00:58:13.260
individuals, the ones who were
third-trimester fetuses then,

00:58:13.260 --> 00:58:17.850
as adults, they have a
19-fold increased incidence

00:58:17.850 --> 00:58:22.520
of obesity, hypertension,
diabetes, and what's

00:58:22.520 --> 00:58:25.580
called metabolic syndrome.

00:58:25.580 --> 00:58:26.990
What's that about?

00:58:26.990 --> 00:58:30.090
Their body has programmed
to be extremely

00:58:30.090 --> 00:58:31.720
thrifty with metabolism.

00:58:31.720 --> 00:58:34.620
And as such, it is
forever after storing

00:58:34.620 --> 00:58:37.970
away every of the
grotesque Westernized diets

00:58:37.970 --> 00:58:39.610
that we all wallow in.

00:58:39.610 --> 00:58:43.150
And what you've got then
is setting individuals

00:58:43.150 --> 00:58:48.610
up for a much, much higher risk
of these metabolic disorders.

00:58:48.610 --> 00:58:52.150
If you were a newborn at
the time, it didn't happen.

00:58:52.150 --> 00:58:54.180
A newborn during
here, the metabolic

00:58:54.180 --> 00:58:55.850
programming is
already over by then.

00:58:55.850 --> 00:58:59.130
If you were a first-trimester
fetus, didn't happen.

00:58:59.130 --> 00:59:01.500
The metabolic programming
hasn't started yet.

00:59:01.500 --> 00:59:04.960
Second, the later part or
second to third trimester

00:59:04.960 --> 00:59:07.600
is when the programming goes on.

00:59:07.600 --> 00:59:10.430
And this was a
landmark observation.

00:59:10.430 --> 00:59:11.980
This was really important.

00:59:11.980 --> 00:59:13.880
Among other things,
you get the people

00:59:13.880 --> 00:59:16.850
who do not like the notion
of these subtle effects.

00:59:16.850 --> 00:59:18.310
And they're saying, OK, sure.

00:59:18.310 --> 00:59:20.520
This can happen,
but this is subtle.

00:59:20.520 --> 00:59:22.980
19-fold is not subtle.

00:59:22.980 --> 00:59:25.930
And this was the
landmark study that

00:59:25.930 --> 00:59:30.800
ushered in what is now called
a whole field of fetal origins

00:59:30.800 --> 00:59:33.080
of adult disease.

00:59:33.080 --> 00:59:35.200
Fetal origins of
adult disease, which

00:59:35.200 --> 00:59:37.850
a lot of realms
of medicine think

00:59:37.850 --> 00:59:40.820
is outrageous and couldn't
possibly work this way.

00:59:40.820 --> 00:59:44.030
And it is popping up in
more and more domains.

00:59:44.030 --> 00:59:47.360
Elevated levels of stress
hormones during fetal life,

00:59:47.360 --> 00:59:50.040
increased likelihood
of anxiety disorders

00:59:50.040 --> 00:59:53.470
as an adult, independent
of post-natal environment.

00:59:53.470 --> 00:59:58.030
Other examples like that, all of
these being ones of programming

00:59:58.030 --> 00:59:59.780
around that time.

00:59:59.780 --> 01:00:03.990
And the Dutch Hunger Winter
one is the iconic example.

01:00:03.990 --> 01:00:06.790
You know, what we're all
accustomed to is yeah,

01:00:06.790 --> 01:00:09.609
you study something
in, like, a planaria.

01:00:09.609 --> 01:00:10.900
And then you study it in a rat.

01:00:10.900 --> 01:00:12.108
And you study it in a monkey.

01:00:12.108 --> 01:00:14.100
And then you study it
in a college freshman.

01:00:14.100 --> 01:00:17.160
And finally, when it's-- now,
you can conclude something

01:00:17.160 --> 01:00:18.860
maybe, maybe about humans.

01:00:18.860 --> 01:00:22.620
This was first discovered in
this population of humans.

01:00:22.620 --> 01:00:25.400
This was no, is this
relevant to humans.

01:00:25.400 --> 01:00:28.220
Interestingly, there
was another population

01:00:28.220 --> 01:00:30.430
at the time that went
through something or other

01:00:30.430 --> 01:00:34.170
like that, which was people
in the city of Stalingrad

01:00:34.170 --> 01:00:36.260
who were under
siege by the Nazis

01:00:36.260 --> 01:00:40.050
and had essentially years
worth of severe starvation.

01:00:40.050 --> 01:00:43.190
They didn't get a Dutch
Hunger Winter phenomenon,

01:00:43.190 --> 01:00:46.360
because the food
coasted off like this.

01:00:46.360 --> 01:00:48.400
And afterward, it
took years for it

01:00:48.400 --> 01:00:50.720
to reach a
Western-European average.

01:00:50.720 --> 01:00:53.070
You don't get it under
those circumstances.

01:00:53.070 --> 01:00:55.960
It's a step function like this.

01:00:55.960 --> 01:00:56.460
OK.

01:00:56.460 --> 01:00:57.910
So think about this now.

01:00:57.910 --> 01:01:00.520
So you were a Dutch
Hunger Winter fetus.

01:01:00.520 --> 01:01:03.400
And as a result, you have
a very thrifty metabolism.

01:01:03.400 --> 01:01:07.370
And 30 years later,
you've gotten pregnant.

01:01:07.370 --> 01:01:09.780
You're having a
perfectly normal diet,

01:01:09.780 --> 01:01:11.690
normal intake of calories.

01:01:11.690 --> 01:01:14.250
But you've got this
thrifty metabolism.

01:01:14.250 --> 01:01:17.510
And as a result,
your body is really

01:01:17.510 --> 01:01:20.480
good at pulling nutrients
out of the bloodstream,

01:01:20.480 --> 01:01:24.310
because you secrete more
insulin than most people would.

01:01:24.310 --> 01:01:26.940
With your thrifty
metabolism, you

01:01:26.940 --> 01:01:30.600
are pulling a disproportionate
share of the calories out

01:01:30.600 --> 01:01:31.590
of the bloodstream.

01:01:31.590 --> 01:01:36.230
And thus, your fetus is getting
a disproportionately smaller

01:01:36.230 --> 01:01:37.800
amount of calories.

01:01:37.800 --> 01:01:41.570
And thus, your fetus is
born with a milder version

01:01:41.570 --> 01:01:44.600
of the Dutch Hunger
Winter phenomenon.

01:01:44.600 --> 01:01:47.510
And this has now been
shown in the grandchildren

01:01:47.510 --> 01:01:49.580
of Dutch Hunger Winter fetuses.

01:01:49.580 --> 01:01:51.920
This is that exact same deal.

01:01:51.920 --> 01:01:55.940
This is non-Mendelian,
non-genetic transmission

01:01:55.940 --> 01:01:58.740
of traits, multigenerationally.

01:01:58.740 --> 01:02:01.510
Absolutely astonishing
that this could work.

01:02:01.510 --> 01:02:04.250
And the biology is
all in place for it.

01:02:04.250 --> 01:02:07.580
What we will see in a little
while is what the mechanism is,

01:02:07.580 --> 01:02:11.170
and it's been identified down
to the molecular level of what

01:02:11.170 --> 01:02:14.700
went on in these Dutch Hunger
Winter-- OK, I'll give it away.

01:02:14.700 --> 01:02:18.110
Remember that epigenetic
business the other day?

01:02:18.110 --> 01:02:22.030
There are epigenetic
changes in the gene's coding

01:02:22.030 --> 01:02:27.370
for things related to insulin in
the Dutch Hunger Winter babies.

01:02:27.370 --> 01:02:29.440
So enormous effect.

01:02:29.440 --> 01:02:32.650
Another example of it,
another dietary one,

01:02:32.650 --> 01:02:35.660
which is, if you are
female-- and female human,

01:02:35.660 --> 01:02:38.540
among other species, this
has been shown in-- there's

01:02:38.540 --> 01:02:42.320
an issue of how much estrogen
does your mother consume

01:02:42.320 --> 01:02:43.950
when you were a fetus.

01:02:43.950 --> 01:02:46.950
Where's estrogen coming
from in the diet?

01:02:46.950 --> 01:02:51.220
From a lot of different types
of plants, phytoestrogens.

01:02:51.220 --> 01:02:54.990
And what the studies show
is that increased exposure

01:02:54.990 --> 01:02:57.580
to estrogen derived
from phytoestrogens

01:02:57.580 --> 01:03:01.230
during fetal life, and there
is a small but consistent

01:03:01.230 --> 01:03:03.650
increased risk of
estrogen-dependent breast

01:03:03.650 --> 01:03:07.910
cancer, 20 years
later, 90 years later.

01:03:07.910 --> 01:03:12.020
Again, very subtle prenatal
environmental effects

01:03:12.020 --> 01:03:17.170
playing out forever, even unto
the generations after you.

01:03:17.170 --> 01:03:20.770
Another realm of prenatal
effects, learning.

01:03:20.770 --> 01:03:23.500
OK, this sounds ludicrous
right off the bat,

01:03:23.500 --> 01:03:26.210
that you can have
learning prenatally.

01:03:26.210 --> 01:03:27.960
You have learning prenatally.

01:03:27.960 --> 01:03:30.790
You can show this first in rats.

01:03:30.790 --> 01:03:32.040
Here's what you do.

01:03:32.040 --> 01:03:36.780
You take a rat fetus, and
you can inject into it

01:03:36.780 --> 01:03:41.260
a particular flavor of
water along with sucrose.

01:03:41.260 --> 01:03:43.220
And the fetus absorbs it.

01:03:43.220 --> 01:03:46.050
The fetus actually drinks
amniotic fluid, which

01:03:46.050 --> 01:03:47.770
I find to be deeply creepy.

01:03:47.770 --> 01:03:50.140
But nonetheless, you
inject this stuff in there.

01:03:50.140 --> 01:03:52.340
And you are doing this a
number of days running.

01:03:52.340 --> 01:03:55.440
And this fetus is now
drinking this flavor that

01:03:55.440 --> 01:03:57.970
has a lot of sucrose in it.

01:03:57.970 --> 01:03:59.450
It tastes good.

01:03:59.450 --> 01:04:00.100
It tastes good?

01:04:00.100 --> 01:04:00.870
You're a fetus.

01:04:00.870 --> 01:04:02.700
What do you mean,
it tastes good?

01:04:02.700 --> 01:04:04.660
The fetus learns about it.

01:04:04.660 --> 01:04:06.960
Because after birth,
given a choice

01:04:06.960 --> 01:04:09.770
between two neutral
flavors, it will

01:04:09.770 --> 01:04:12.740
prefer the flavor it was
exposed to that it was

01:04:12.740 --> 01:04:14.990
drinking when it was a fetus.

01:04:14.990 --> 01:04:17.520
How weird is that?

01:04:17.520 --> 01:04:19.770
More ones-- more ones?

01:04:19.770 --> 01:04:21.030
OK, that was good grammar.

01:04:21.030 --> 01:04:21.720
More ones.

01:04:21.720 --> 01:04:23.130
Here's one from humans.

01:04:23.130 --> 01:04:27.000
And this was a study,
which is as strange

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:29.090
as you can get,
looking at the fact

01:04:29.090 --> 01:04:32.690
that the diaphragm is
a very good resonating

01:04:32.690 --> 01:04:34.660
membrane, something or other.

01:04:34.660 --> 01:04:39.360
Mother's voices are heard in
the fetal sack quite readily.

01:04:39.360 --> 01:04:42.210
And if I don't know how they
got the fiber-optic camera

01:04:42.210 --> 01:04:44.510
in there, I have no idea
how they got the microphones

01:04:44.510 --> 01:04:45.990
in there for recording that.

01:04:45.990 --> 01:04:49.990
But it is a very resonant
chamber, the diaphragm

01:04:49.990 --> 01:04:51.630
and the amniotic fluid.

01:04:51.630 --> 01:04:55.380
Fetuses hear a lot of
what's going on out there,

01:04:55.380 --> 01:04:57.910
most notably mom's voice.

01:04:57.910 --> 01:05:01.220
So this was a study, a
totally inspired one.

01:05:01.220 --> 01:05:03.990
And what you had
was, in this one,

01:05:03.990 --> 01:05:06.770
pregnant women spent
their last trimester

01:05:06.770 --> 01:05:10.130
loudly reading either
The Cat in the Hat

01:05:10.130 --> 01:05:12.480
over and over, like
four times a day

01:05:12.480 --> 01:05:15.530
or something, until they
went mad, absolutely mad--

01:05:15.530 --> 01:05:17.310
and that's before the
kid was even born--

01:05:17.310 --> 01:05:21.400
or reading some random
collection of sentences that

01:05:21.400 --> 01:05:24.690
controlled for word length,
that controlled for rhythmicity,

01:05:24.690 --> 01:05:26.310
all of that.

01:05:26.310 --> 01:05:29.880
Then, you get the
newborn some time later,

01:05:29.880 --> 01:05:35.530
and you give them a test of
which they prefer to listen to.

01:05:35.530 --> 01:05:37.960
How do you do that
with a newborn?

01:05:37.960 --> 01:05:41.650
Something you can do is,
when newborns like something,

01:05:41.650 --> 01:05:44.860
they make more sucking
motions with their mouth.

01:05:44.860 --> 01:05:49.490
So you've got a sucko-meter
thing in there measuring it.

01:05:49.490 --> 01:05:53.760
And the newborns prefer
hearing The Cat in the Hat.

01:05:53.760 --> 01:05:55.570
They learned it.

01:05:55.570 --> 01:05:57.640
Not a huge effect,
but nonetheless,

01:05:57.640 --> 01:05:59.170
what is up with that?

01:05:59.170 --> 01:06:01.670
Of course, a follow-up question
that maybe half the people

01:06:01.670 --> 01:06:04.430
in here would be wondering is,
well, what about the fathers?

01:06:04.430 --> 01:06:07.580
And they have the study with the
fathers reading Cat In The Hat

01:06:07.580 --> 01:06:11.690
and, you know, like a megaphone
on mom's belly and reading.

01:06:11.690 --> 01:06:13.250
And it doesn't work.

01:06:13.250 --> 01:06:15.340
It doesn't resonate
enough that side.

01:06:15.340 --> 01:06:17.590
Sounds from the mother.

01:06:17.590 --> 01:06:22.060
OK, so what we see here is this
whole world of stuff going on

01:06:22.060 --> 01:06:25.300
before behavior geneticists
show up and say,

01:06:25.300 --> 01:06:26.960
environment is just started.

01:06:26.960 --> 01:06:30.070
All these prenatal
effects of hormones,

01:06:30.070 --> 01:06:34.430
nutrition, sensory stimulation,
amazing, in some cases,

01:06:34.430 --> 01:06:35.510
multigenerational.

01:06:35.510 --> 01:06:36.102
Yeah?

01:06:36.102 --> 01:06:37.935
Did they catch up with
those children later,

01:06:37.935 --> 01:06:39.768
The Cat in the Hat
children, and see if they

01:06:39.768 --> 01:06:41.710
had a tendency to rhyme more?

01:06:41.710 --> 01:06:43.700
[LAUGHTER]

01:06:43.700 --> 01:06:45.310
Where are they now?

01:06:45.310 --> 01:06:49.406
Remarkably, all of them are
heads of states of countries.

01:06:49.406 --> 01:06:50.672
[LAUGHTER]

01:06:50.672 --> 01:06:52.630
People are still trying
to understand that one.

01:06:52.630 --> 01:06:55.310
But very good
follow-ups on that.

01:06:55.310 --> 01:06:58.610
So we've got this punch
line here, over and over,

01:06:58.610 --> 01:07:01.580
showing the power
of prenatal effects.

01:07:01.580 --> 01:07:02.730
One final study.

01:07:02.730 --> 01:07:05.670
And this was one carried out by
a scientist at Berkeley named,

01:07:05.670 --> 01:07:10.110
Darlene Francis, which took
some amazing surgical skills.

01:07:10.110 --> 01:07:13.210
So there are different
strains of rats

01:07:13.210 --> 01:07:17.190
that have been bred for
different levels of anxiety.

01:07:17.190 --> 01:07:20.250
And we've already heard about
one possibility for that.

01:07:20.250 --> 01:07:22.270
It turns out some
genetic differences

01:07:22.270 --> 01:07:25.780
in the promoter to the gene for
the benzodiazepine receptor.

01:07:25.780 --> 01:07:27.160
There's all sorts
of strains that

01:07:27.160 --> 01:07:29.710
have been bred for high,
low levels of anxiety

01:07:29.710 --> 01:07:31.100
that people have studied.

01:07:31.100 --> 01:07:32.610
They've been bred.

01:07:32.610 --> 01:07:34.950
These are transmissible traits.

01:07:34.950 --> 01:07:37.810
These are heritable,
these are genetic traits.

01:07:37.810 --> 01:07:40.870
Here's what Darlene
Francis did, which

01:07:40.870 --> 01:07:42.810
was she did an adoption study.

01:07:42.810 --> 01:07:45.400
What's the adoption paradigm
we've heard already?

01:07:45.400 --> 01:07:48.250
Right after birth, you
cross-foster the rats,

01:07:48.250 --> 01:07:50.040
or the kids get adopted.

01:07:50.040 --> 01:07:52.400
That's not the
adoption study she did.

01:07:52.400 --> 01:07:55.030
She transferred fetuses.

01:07:55.030 --> 01:07:57.480
She figured out how
to do the surgery

01:07:57.480 --> 01:08:00.890
to remove a fetus early on
in development from one rat

01:08:00.890 --> 01:08:04.240
mom to another rat mom where
they developed perfectly

01:08:04.240 --> 01:08:06.390
normally, once she
had this surgery down.

01:08:06.390 --> 01:08:08.850
And you know what turns
out to be the case?

01:08:08.850 --> 01:08:11.120
It's not a genetic trait.

01:08:11.120 --> 01:08:12.670
It was not a genetic trait.

01:08:12.670 --> 01:08:15.620
You grew up with
the anxiety levels

01:08:15.620 --> 01:08:18.120
matching the strain
of your mother,

01:08:18.120 --> 01:08:22.500
even if the strain of the
individual whose body you

01:08:22.500 --> 01:08:26.359
fetally developed in-- you take
a mom from the high anxiety

01:08:26.359 --> 01:08:29.689
strain, and you take a mom
from the low anxiety strain.

01:08:29.689 --> 01:08:32.370
And you take fetuses from
the high anxiety mom,

01:08:32.370 --> 01:08:35.359
and they go through gestation
in the low anxiety mom.

01:08:35.359 --> 01:08:38.200
And as adults, they
are low anxiety.

01:08:38.200 --> 01:08:42.200
It was not a genetic trait,
it was a prenatal one

01:08:42.200 --> 01:08:46.569
having to do with another one
of those multigenerational

01:08:46.569 --> 01:08:50.700
begatting by having early
experience influencing

01:08:50.700 --> 01:08:53.080
the nature of the pregnancy
you would eventually have,

01:08:53.080 --> 01:08:55.189
and thus, influencing
your fetus,

01:08:55.189 --> 01:08:58.100
producing a different pregnancy
for them down the line.

01:08:58.100 --> 01:09:00.819
This demonstration
of cross-fostering,

01:09:00.819 --> 01:09:04.220
of adopting, as early
as you possibly could,

01:09:04.220 --> 01:09:05.930
enormously important study.

01:09:05.930 --> 01:09:08.189
One really difficult one.

01:09:08.189 --> 01:09:11.380
Yet another wave pounding
on this point, environment

01:09:11.380 --> 01:09:13.180
does not begin at birth.

01:09:13.180 --> 01:09:15.300
And some of the most
important environment

01:09:15.300 --> 01:09:18.020
is not occurring
starting at birth.

01:09:18.020 --> 01:09:20.590
And everything about
behavior genetics,

01:09:20.590 --> 01:09:23.840
classically, was
predicated on there's

01:09:23.840 --> 01:09:25.609
no environment before that.

01:09:25.609 --> 01:09:27.430
OK, so what do they
come back with?

01:09:27.430 --> 01:09:28.620
What's the response?

01:09:28.620 --> 01:09:30.399
We've already seen
a possible way

01:09:30.399 --> 01:09:35.260
of controlling for that, which
is, if you see traits shared

01:09:35.260 --> 01:09:38.590
in common with the
biological father,

01:09:38.590 --> 01:09:40.580
and then you see
more traits shared

01:09:40.580 --> 01:09:43.520
in common with the biological
mother, the increased

01:09:43.520 --> 01:09:48.060
degree of sharedness with the
mom reflects, not the genes,

01:09:48.060 --> 01:09:50.810
because you're getting
the same amount of genes

01:09:50.810 --> 01:09:51.779
from each parent.

01:09:51.779 --> 01:09:54.260
It reflects the
prenatal environment.

01:09:54.260 --> 01:09:57.830
That would be the control that
would be used in these studies.

01:09:57.830 --> 01:09:59.750
The extent to which
a trait is more

01:09:59.750 --> 01:10:03.890
shared with a biological mother
than with a biological father

01:10:03.890 --> 01:10:06.780
is a reflection of
prenatal effects,

01:10:06.780 --> 01:10:10.920
because you get the same amount
of genes from each parent.

01:10:10.920 --> 01:10:15.320
Naturally, this turns out to
be vastly messier than this.

01:10:15.320 --> 01:10:17.080
Because there's a
whole world in which

01:10:17.080 --> 01:10:20.190
you're getting more genetic
influences from your mother

01:10:20.190 --> 01:10:21.910
than from your father.

01:10:21.910 --> 01:10:22.770
OK.

01:10:22.770 --> 01:10:24.926
First one is, once
again, if it turns out

01:10:24.926 --> 01:10:27.300
the person who's claiming to
be the father isn't actually

01:10:27.300 --> 01:10:30.120
the father, that kind of
changes the whole map.

01:10:30.120 --> 01:10:32.120
And once again,
that is a problem

01:10:32.120 --> 01:10:35.300
running through all of human
behavior genetics literature.

01:10:35.300 --> 01:10:38.010
But here, here's the next one.

01:10:38.010 --> 01:10:41.230
Here, we have-- just make sure
we've got our cliche in place

01:10:41.230 --> 01:10:43.330
here-- what is this?

01:10:43.330 --> 01:10:44.547
This is the--

01:10:47.290 --> 01:10:49.990
OK, which is the
what of the cell?

01:10:49.990 --> 01:10:50.720
Powerhouse,

01:10:50.720 --> 01:10:51.540
The powerhouse.

01:10:51.540 --> 01:10:55.010
OK, here we have the powerhouse
of the cell, mitochondria.

01:10:55.010 --> 01:10:58.210
And in this rather odd cell,
there's one mitochondrion,

01:10:58.210 --> 01:11:01.220
but it is standing in for
all of the powerhouses.

01:11:01.220 --> 01:11:03.020
And we've got mitochondria.

01:11:03.020 --> 01:11:05.420
Something that, when you
first learn about this,

01:11:05.420 --> 01:11:08.380
is just flabbergasting,
which is, here

01:11:08.380 --> 01:11:11.650
you've got a cell with
its DNA, and its nucleus,

01:11:11.650 --> 01:11:14.300
and its double helix
thingy happening there.

01:11:14.300 --> 01:11:16.530
And it turns out
that mitochondria

01:11:16.530 --> 01:11:19.440
have their own DNA.

01:11:19.440 --> 01:11:21.660
And this is part
of explaining one

01:11:21.660 --> 01:11:26.930
of the, like, truly amazing,
adventurous, nutty ideas

01:11:26.930 --> 01:11:28.470
that have turned out to be true.

01:11:28.470 --> 01:11:31.790
Scientist, named Lynn Margulis,
University of Massachusetts,

01:11:31.790 --> 01:11:36.090
30 years ago or so, she
noted that this business

01:11:36.090 --> 01:11:38.850
of mitochondria
having their own DNA,

01:11:38.850 --> 01:11:42.240
and came up with this hypothesis
that mitochondria used

01:11:42.240 --> 01:11:44.410
to be independent organisms.

01:11:44.410 --> 01:11:47.480
That in some symbiotic
whatever, billions of years

01:11:47.480 --> 01:11:51.870
ago, got into cells that had
no mitochrondia at the time,

01:11:51.870 --> 01:11:54.900
and that there's been
a symbiosis ever since.

01:11:54.900 --> 01:11:57.590
Mitochondria have
DNA, which are related

01:11:57.590 --> 01:12:00.010
to mitochondrial function.

01:12:00.010 --> 01:12:02.920
Not a ton of the
stuff, nonetheless, you

01:12:02.920 --> 01:12:06.307
have every gene that is critical
for mitochondrial function.

01:12:06.307 --> 01:12:07.140
No, that's not true.

01:12:07.140 --> 01:12:08.910
A few of them have
wound up in here.

01:12:08.910 --> 01:12:11.060
But all of the genes
in here are pretty

01:12:11.060 --> 01:12:13.610
important for
mitochondrial powerhousing,

01:12:13.610 --> 01:12:14.890
all that sort of thing.

01:12:14.890 --> 01:12:19.950
And these are derived from
a completely different world

01:12:19.950 --> 01:12:22.590
of DNA than these.

01:12:22.590 --> 01:12:24.570
So now consider this.

01:12:24.570 --> 01:12:27.580
This cell is an egg.

01:12:27.580 --> 01:12:30.600
This cell is not an egg.

01:12:30.600 --> 01:12:36.990
This cell is just merely
carrying genetic information

01:12:36.990 --> 01:12:38.430
that looks like that.

01:12:38.430 --> 01:12:42.140
What you've got is sperm,
all they are carrying

01:12:42.140 --> 01:12:46.430
are the DNAs, the
genes, the DNA.

01:12:46.430 --> 01:12:50.560
And they don't have cytoplasm,
the fluid-y environment

01:12:50.560 --> 01:12:51.430
in a cell.

01:12:51.430 --> 01:12:54.240
This is one major
dense packing job.

01:12:54.240 --> 01:12:56.800
Here's the critical implication.

01:12:56.800 --> 01:13:02.520
Eggs have mitochondria,
sperm don't.

01:13:02.520 --> 01:13:05.420
So right at the point
of fertilization,

01:13:05.420 --> 01:13:10.710
you have gotten all of your
mitochondria from your mother.

01:13:10.710 --> 01:13:13.430
And thus, all of
the genes related

01:13:13.430 --> 01:13:15.360
to mitochondrial
function that are

01:13:15.360 --> 01:13:19.160
contained in the mitochondria
you don't get from fathers.

01:13:19.160 --> 01:13:22.220
It is exclusively
inherited from mothers.

01:13:22.220 --> 01:13:26.690
Mitochondrial DNA solely
comes from the mother.

01:13:26.690 --> 01:13:28.730
So what we've just
seen as a first pass

01:13:28.730 --> 01:13:31.650
is it's not an even 50/50 split.

01:13:31.650 --> 01:13:34.380
You get a disproportionate
share of your DNA

01:13:34.380 --> 01:13:36.180
coming from the mother.

01:13:36.180 --> 01:13:37.500
Really important.

01:13:37.500 --> 01:13:39.320
And one that's been
used by all sorts

01:13:39.320 --> 01:13:42.990
of evolutionary geneticists
to trace legacies.

01:13:42.990 --> 01:13:48.410
If these mitochondrial DNA is
only passed along female lines,

01:13:48.410 --> 01:13:51.210
that allows you to figure
out all sorts of stuff

01:13:51.210 --> 01:13:52.420
about evolution.

01:13:52.420 --> 01:13:56.430
It has given rise to the Eve
hypothesis, that somewhere back

01:13:56.430 --> 01:14:00.700
then was a woman, probably
some sort of early hominid,

01:14:00.700 --> 01:14:05.380
who is ultimately the ancestor,
the great, great, great, great,

01:14:05.380 --> 01:14:08.330
great, grandmother of every
single human on Earth.

01:14:08.330 --> 01:14:12.160
And it can be traced through
the mitochondrial DNA.

01:14:12.160 --> 01:14:14.030
So that's an asymmetry.

01:14:14.030 --> 01:14:15.020
Next one.

01:14:15.020 --> 01:14:18.320
Next source of asymmetry
is back to that business

01:14:18.320 --> 01:14:20.290
about imprinted genes.

01:14:20.290 --> 01:14:22.270
From a couple of weeks
ago, you remember

01:14:22.270 --> 01:14:25.140
that one, genes that
are working differently,

01:14:25.140 --> 01:14:28.210
depending on which parent
you are getting them from.

01:14:28.210 --> 01:14:30.970
So that one's a violation
as well of this rule

01:14:30.970 --> 01:14:35.230
that you get all of your DNA in
equal amounts from each parent.

01:14:35.230 --> 01:14:39.050
This is another thing that
possibly skews the ratio.

01:14:39.050 --> 01:14:42.090
Now, here's another
very interesting thing.

01:14:42.090 --> 01:14:44.170
So you've got the egg here.

01:14:44.170 --> 01:14:47.690
And not only does it have this
cytoplasm with mitochondria

01:14:47.690 --> 01:14:51.110
floating around,
but in addition,

01:14:51.110 --> 01:14:53.130
there's other stuff
floating around in there,

01:14:53.130 --> 01:14:56.290
like transcription factors.

01:14:56.290 --> 01:14:59.190
Sperm don't have
transcription factors.

01:14:59.190 --> 01:15:02.480
Sperm, all they're doing is on
this, like, suicide swimming

01:15:02.480 --> 01:15:03.350
mission there.

01:15:03.350 --> 01:15:05.000
And they're not
making any new genes.

01:15:05.000 --> 01:15:07.700
All they're doing is
this one, long spurt

01:15:07.700 --> 01:15:09.700
of racing for the end.

01:15:09.700 --> 01:15:12.160
And in the case of
the eggs, though, you

01:15:12.160 --> 01:15:14.000
have transcription factors.

01:15:14.000 --> 01:15:17.430
You have all sorts of
proteins in the cytoplasm.

01:15:17.430 --> 01:15:20.750
You've got a fully functioning
cell, instead of this, sort of,

01:15:20.750 --> 01:15:23.520
much more streamlined version.

01:15:23.520 --> 01:15:28.430
All the transcription factors
that come in a fertilized egg

01:15:28.430 --> 01:15:31.130
are coming from the mother.

01:15:31.130 --> 01:15:33.542
So what does that
wind up meaning?

01:15:33.542 --> 01:15:36.120
Transcription factors,
those are proteins.

01:15:36.120 --> 01:15:37.580
We're not talking
about genes here.

01:15:37.580 --> 01:15:39.560
We just saw how
you get more genes

01:15:39.560 --> 01:15:41.140
from your mother
than your father,

01:15:41.140 --> 01:15:42.940
these mitochondrial genes.

01:15:42.940 --> 01:15:45.590
OK, but transcription
factors, the father

01:15:45.590 --> 01:15:47.310
has genes for
transcription factors.

01:15:47.310 --> 01:15:49.520
The mother has genes for
transcription factors.

01:15:49.520 --> 01:15:52.840
What's the significance of
getting your transcription

01:15:52.840 --> 01:15:56.850
factors from your mother
in the fertilized egg?

01:15:56.850 --> 01:15:57.630
OK.

01:15:57.630 --> 01:16:01.200
Consider here two genes.

01:16:01.200 --> 01:16:05.950
The first one codes for
transcription factor A.

01:16:05.950 --> 01:16:06.930
We know that already.

01:16:06.930 --> 01:16:08.940
Transcription factors
are typically proteins,

01:16:08.940 --> 01:16:11.070
so they have their own
genes all the way down.

01:16:11.070 --> 01:16:16.600
And this codes for gene
X, whatever that is.

01:16:16.600 --> 01:16:19.120
So here's what you've got.

01:16:19.120 --> 01:16:25.760
There are promoters responsive
to transcription factor A.

01:16:25.760 --> 01:16:29.950
Transcription factor A turns
on the synthesis of the protein

01:16:29.950 --> 01:16:32.550
coded for by gene
X. And in addition,

01:16:32.550 --> 01:16:37.060
transcription factor A turns
on transcription factor A gene.

01:16:37.060 --> 01:16:39.130
It's a positive feedback
loop where it makes

01:16:39.130 --> 01:16:40.720
more and more of the stuff.

01:16:40.720 --> 01:16:43.950
That's the way this particular
transcription factor works.

01:16:43.950 --> 01:16:46.870
So suppose this is
the only thing that

01:16:46.870 --> 01:16:51.570
can activate transcription
of gene X. So

01:16:51.570 --> 01:16:55.210
suppose you've got some
environmental event which,

01:16:55.210 --> 01:16:59.540
as a result of it, knocks out
the activity of transcription

01:16:59.540 --> 01:17:04.220
factor X in an egg.

01:17:04.220 --> 01:17:05.560
The egg is fertilized.

01:17:05.560 --> 01:17:12.540
And as a result of transcription
factor A not being expressed,

01:17:12.540 --> 01:17:13.740
it doesn't express more.

01:17:13.740 --> 01:17:16.090
This is the only thing that
drives more expression.

01:17:16.090 --> 01:17:19.490
And you never make gene X.

01:17:19.490 --> 01:17:22.640
Now, somewhere along
the line in your body,

01:17:22.640 --> 01:17:26.650
you are soon making eggs
which contain these genes,

01:17:26.650 --> 01:17:29.270
of course, but
where you have never

01:17:29.270 --> 01:17:33.620
expressed transcription factor
A, because this was knocked out

01:17:33.620 --> 01:17:34.440
in the egg.

01:17:34.440 --> 01:17:38.540
So because of that, you
never express gene X.

01:17:38.540 --> 01:17:40.230
And that egg gets fertilized.

01:17:40.230 --> 01:17:43.660
And you pass on that
trait to your offspring.

01:17:43.660 --> 01:17:48.880
You pass that on, this
acquired trait of transcription

01:17:48.880 --> 01:17:50.380
factor A not working.

01:17:50.380 --> 01:17:52.890
If this is the
circuitry that you have,

01:17:52.890 --> 01:17:56.520
it doesn't matter which
version of gene X you get,

01:17:56.520 --> 01:17:59.720
you are never going to express
that gene for generations

01:17:59.720 --> 01:18:03.010
and generations, forever,
if this is the loop.

01:18:03.010 --> 01:18:06.830
What's going on here, what a
lot of people think is relevant,

01:18:06.830 --> 01:18:09.710
are some environmental
toxins that

01:18:09.710 --> 01:18:11.920
are known to
disrupt the activity

01:18:11.920 --> 01:18:13.970
of certain
transcription factors.

01:18:13.970 --> 01:18:17.740
And what that does is
induce heritability

01:18:17.740 --> 01:18:21.180
in a non-genetic way of
non-expressing of a gene.

01:18:21.180 --> 01:18:24.020
The gene's being inherited,
but it will never ever

01:18:24.020 --> 01:18:25.000
be expressed.

01:18:25.000 --> 01:18:27.000
What have you just acquired?

01:18:27.000 --> 01:18:29.390
A Lamarckian trait.

01:18:29.390 --> 01:18:30.650
You remember Lamarck.

01:18:30.650 --> 01:18:33.880
Everybody learns about Lamarck,
in order to mock him viciously.

01:18:33.880 --> 01:18:37.430
And Lamarck had the notion that
the way evolutionary change

01:18:37.430 --> 01:18:39.220
works, the way
inheritance works,

01:18:39.220 --> 01:18:41.660
is you experience
something, and it

01:18:41.660 --> 01:18:43.490
causes a change in your body.

01:18:43.490 --> 01:18:46.800
And as a result, you pass
on that acquired trait

01:18:46.800 --> 01:18:48.280
to your offspring.

01:18:48.280 --> 01:18:49.020
Ludicrous.

01:18:49.020 --> 01:18:52.580
Lamarckians have been mocked
and pilloried for centuries,

01:18:52.580 --> 01:18:56.300
except in the Soviet Union in
the 1930s, where it gave rise

01:18:56.300 --> 01:19:00.580
to Lysenkoism, a very horrific
piece of genetic history.

01:19:00.580 --> 01:19:03.120
But what you've got is
this complete trashing

01:19:03.120 --> 01:19:05.810
of the notion of you
acquire some trait

01:19:05.810 --> 01:19:09.620
from the environment, and you
pass it on to your offspring.

01:19:09.620 --> 01:19:12.400
This is Lamarckian inheritance.

01:19:12.400 --> 01:19:15.650
This is an environmental factor
that knocks this transcription

01:19:15.650 --> 01:19:17.210
factor out of action.

01:19:17.210 --> 01:19:20.020
And if this is the
wiring that you've got,

01:19:20.020 --> 01:19:22.360
this gene will
never be expressed.

01:19:22.360 --> 01:19:25.350
And as a result, it will never
be expressed in your offspring,

01:19:25.350 --> 01:19:27.830
in your grandkids, et
cetera, all the way down.

01:19:27.830 --> 01:19:30.670
This is Lamarckian
inheritance of a trait.

01:19:30.670 --> 01:19:33.770
And again, where the best
evidence for this has been

01:19:33.770 --> 01:19:37.040
is with environmental
toxins that knock out,

01:19:37.040 --> 01:19:40.750
that have some of these
mutating effects in eggs.

01:19:40.750 --> 01:19:44.200
They are not mutations
in a classical DNA sense.

01:19:44.200 --> 01:19:46.660
But nonetheless, they
are now heritable.

01:19:46.660 --> 01:19:48.830
So that pops up also.

01:19:48.830 --> 01:19:50.160
So have we got here?

01:19:50.160 --> 01:19:52.370
We have the simple
assumption that,

01:19:52.370 --> 01:19:56.150
if you see more sharing
of a trait with the mother

01:19:56.150 --> 01:19:57.920
than with the father,
that's reflecting

01:19:57.920 --> 01:19:59.420
prenatal environment.

01:19:59.420 --> 01:20:01.250
And what we've seen
here is totally

01:20:01.250 --> 01:20:04.110
messing this up is the
fact that you do not

01:20:04.110 --> 01:20:07.280
get equal genetic
influences from each parent.

01:20:07.280 --> 01:20:09.420
You are getting more
genetic material,

01:20:09.420 --> 01:20:11.660
you are getting more
genes from your mother,

01:20:11.660 --> 01:20:15.090
because the mitochondrial DNA.

01:20:15.090 --> 01:20:17.700
Even if you are getting
equal amounts of DNA,

01:20:17.700 --> 01:20:20.210
expression of them will
have different consequences

01:20:20.210 --> 01:20:23.160
because of imprinted genes.

01:20:23.160 --> 01:20:25.430
Finally, in this
world, having nothing

01:20:25.430 --> 01:20:29.710
to do with the amount of
genes or the actual DNA,

01:20:29.710 --> 01:20:32.160
you can have this
Lamarckian inheritance

01:20:32.160 --> 01:20:35.220
of traits due to
environmental perturbations.

01:20:35.220 --> 01:20:37.220
What we see here
are ways ranging

01:20:37.220 --> 01:20:41.320
from extremely subtle and rare
to some rather substantial ones

01:20:41.320 --> 01:20:44.710
with the mitochondria where
you are not getting equivalent

01:20:44.710 --> 01:20:46.660
inheritance from both parents.

01:20:46.660 --> 01:20:49.300
So that confuses things a lot.

01:20:49.300 --> 01:20:50.210
OK.

01:20:50.210 --> 01:20:53.640
So after all of that,
you do, nonetheless,

01:20:53.640 --> 01:20:57.610
get circumstances where
behavior is influenced by genes.

01:20:57.610 --> 01:21:00.270
And by every rule,
it could be shown.

01:21:00.270 --> 01:21:02.580
And by the most
contemporary of techniques

01:21:02.580 --> 01:21:05.510
where people find
the gene and the DNA,

01:21:05.510 --> 01:21:08.370
and they've traced out the steps
in showing that there really

01:21:08.370 --> 01:21:11.050
are genetic influences
on behavior,

01:21:11.050 --> 01:21:15.170
and ones that withstand every
single one of these criticisms.

01:21:15.170 --> 01:21:15.770
OK.

01:21:15.770 --> 01:21:18.400
So sometimes, you've
got genes regulating

01:21:18.400 --> 01:21:20.750
or genes influencing behavior.

01:21:20.750 --> 01:21:23.670
But now we bring in a
whole other possibility.

01:21:23.670 --> 01:21:25.410
And this is something
that was emphasized

01:21:25.410 --> 01:21:29.390
by a psychologist named, Judith
Rich Harris, a number of years

01:21:29.390 --> 01:21:33.000
ago, in a very important book
of hers, called The Nurture

01:21:33.000 --> 01:21:36.420
Assumption, which has a
lot to do with arguing

01:21:36.420 --> 01:21:38.320
the relative importance
of influences

01:21:38.320 --> 01:21:40.000
of peer versus parents.

01:21:40.000 --> 01:21:41.930
Nonetheless, she
focused in one section

01:21:41.930 --> 01:21:44.750
of the book on the
genetics of behavior

01:21:44.750 --> 01:21:49.580
and focused on what she calls
indirect genetic effects.

01:21:49.580 --> 01:21:52.560
What would indirect
genetic effects be?

01:21:52.560 --> 01:21:53.450
OK.

01:21:53.450 --> 01:21:55.270
You've got that
trait that I referred

01:21:55.270 --> 01:21:57.560
to before, one of
the most reliable

01:21:57.560 --> 01:22:00.070
of traits in the
identical twins separated

01:22:00.070 --> 01:22:03.590
at birth business, 50%
heritability of where

01:22:03.590 --> 01:22:09.410
you are on the introversion,
extroversion continuum.

01:22:09.410 --> 01:22:10.430
OK.

01:22:10.430 --> 01:22:12.650
So that one has
held up pretty well.

01:22:12.650 --> 01:22:16.450
Amid all the possible complaints
about these various approaches,

01:22:16.450 --> 01:22:18.440
that one appears
to be quite solid.

01:22:18.440 --> 01:22:20.780
And you're immediately
off and running

01:22:20.780 --> 01:22:26.270
with, OK, genes for
extroversion, for sociality,

01:22:26.270 --> 01:22:27.330
for all of that.

01:22:27.330 --> 01:22:31.010
What she shows instead is
something else is happening.

01:22:31.010 --> 01:22:37.180
There's a very, very heritable
trait from parent to offspring,

01:22:37.180 --> 01:22:40.030
one of the most heritable
physical traits out there,

01:22:40.030 --> 01:22:45.440
which is your height and
your appearance in general,

01:22:45.440 --> 01:22:48.300
that those are highly
heritable traits.

01:22:48.300 --> 01:22:51.900
And suddenly, you
have a phenomenon that

01:22:51.900 --> 01:22:54.910
is well-documented,
which is people

01:22:54.910 --> 01:22:58.360
who are taller are treated
better and considered

01:22:58.360 --> 01:23:01.608
more attractive, comma,
he says bitterly.

01:23:01.608 --> 01:23:03.090
[LAUGHTER]

01:23:03.090 --> 01:23:05.940
What you've got is people
are treated differently

01:23:05.940 --> 01:23:07.480
along those lines.

01:23:07.480 --> 01:23:09.980
And what is known
also is, people

01:23:09.980 --> 01:23:13.510
who are treated more
positively during development,

01:23:13.510 --> 01:23:17.170
during childhood,
become more extroverted.

01:23:17.170 --> 01:23:21.330
What we have here is not
heritability of the trait

01:23:21.330 --> 01:23:22.810
where you are in
the introversion,

01:23:22.810 --> 01:23:24.430
extroversion continuum.

01:23:24.430 --> 01:23:28.440
What you have is heritability
of a physical trait, which

01:23:28.440 --> 01:23:30.200
causes you to be
treated differently

01:23:30.200 --> 01:23:34.610
in the world, which then brings
about changes in personality.

01:23:34.610 --> 01:23:37.490
And studies have
since shown that most

01:23:37.490 --> 01:23:40.480
of the heritability of the
introversion, extroversion

01:23:40.480 --> 01:23:44.380
is mediated by physical
traits in between.

01:23:44.380 --> 01:23:47.530
So that's a completely
indirect way in which

01:23:47.530 --> 01:23:49.690
you could have gotten to this.

01:23:49.690 --> 01:23:50.880
More cases.

01:23:50.880 --> 01:23:52.300
More cases of this.

01:23:52.300 --> 01:23:53.720
Let's see.

01:23:53.720 --> 01:24:00.810
OK, you can show, in various
bird, turkey, hen species,

01:24:00.810 --> 01:24:04.390
that there are chicks, that
there is heritability of rank.

01:24:04.390 --> 01:24:06.990
You could be born
to a low-ranking mom

01:24:06.990 --> 01:24:08.890
in the pecking
order, high-ranking,

01:24:08.890 --> 01:24:11.350
all the perfect
studies, and controls,

01:24:11.350 --> 01:24:13.170
and cross-fostering,
all of that,

01:24:13.170 --> 01:24:16.110
and there is
heritability of rank.

01:24:16.110 --> 01:24:18.310
But another indirect
genetic effect

01:24:18.310 --> 01:24:20.950
that was subsequently
demonstrated, which is it's

01:24:20.950 --> 01:24:23.160
not the rank that's
being inherited,

01:24:23.160 --> 01:24:25.160
it's a particular
version of genes

01:24:25.160 --> 01:24:29.560
related to melanism of
your feathers, the color

01:24:29.560 --> 01:24:31.640
and iridescence
of your feathers.

01:24:31.640 --> 01:24:34.930
And it turns out, if you have
a certain color pattern, all

01:24:34.930 --> 01:24:37.160
the other like
roosters, and chicks,

01:24:37.160 --> 01:24:40.690
and hens, and poultry,
peck at you more often.

01:24:40.690 --> 01:24:43.290
And you're reduced
to subordination.

01:24:43.290 --> 01:24:47.100
This is not inheritance
of a social dominant trait

01:24:47.100 --> 01:24:49.080
or a social subordination trait.

01:24:49.080 --> 01:24:50.930
This is inheritance
of a gene having

01:24:50.930 --> 01:24:54.420
to do with the color and
iridescence of your feathers,

01:24:54.420 --> 01:24:57.990
which wind up producing
your social rank.

01:24:57.990 --> 01:24:59.510
Another example.

01:24:59.510 --> 01:25:00.670
Here's another one.

01:25:00.670 --> 01:25:03.660
OK, back to chicks
again, which is chicks

01:25:03.660 --> 01:25:08.220
appear to be intuitively
able to peck at grubs shortly

01:25:08.220 --> 01:25:09.470
after birth.

01:25:09.470 --> 01:25:11.790
That they're able to
peck down and get grubs.

01:25:11.790 --> 01:25:14.240
And by all the rules
of behavior genetics,

01:25:14.240 --> 01:25:16.940
with all the constraints
and criticisms answered,

01:25:16.940 --> 01:25:19.710
this appears to be
a heritable trait.

01:25:19.710 --> 01:25:22.750
But it turns out that this
is not what is heritable.

01:25:22.750 --> 01:25:27.470
What is heritable, bizarrely, is
the tendency of newborn chicks

01:25:27.470 --> 01:25:30.280
to find their toes to
be very interesting

01:25:30.280 --> 01:25:32.170
and to peck at their toes.

01:25:32.170 --> 01:25:35.260
And they quickly learn that this
doesn't feel all that great.

01:25:35.260 --> 01:25:37.744
But if you do it in somewhat
more sloppy of a way,

01:25:37.744 --> 01:25:39.160
you get one of
these things that's

01:25:39.160 --> 01:25:41.300
squirmy that tastes good.

01:25:41.300 --> 01:25:44.190
They start off, what is
genetic is the tendency

01:25:44.190 --> 01:25:47.160
to peck at your feet.

01:25:47.160 --> 01:25:48.050
God knows why.

01:25:48.050 --> 01:25:50.220
If you are a newborn
chick, because

01:25:50.220 --> 01:25:53.360
of extremely elegant
high technology

01:25:53.360 --> 01:25:56.210
studies in which newborn
chicks are put in galoshes

01:25:56.210 --> 01:25:57.850
or something and
they don't pack,

01:25:57.850 --> 01:26:01.490
and they don't show the
seemingly innate ability to

01:26:01.490 --> 01:26:03.020
peck for grubs.

01:26:03.020 --> 01:26:05.100
So here, we have
a behavioral trait

01:26:05.100 --> 01:26:09.820
which, in fact, is indirectly
mediated by something else.

01:26:09.820 --> 01:26:11.210
More examples.

01:26:11.210 --> 01:26:16.250
There is, by now, a literature
showing approximately 70%

01:26:16.250 --> 01:26:19.680
heritability-- and I
keep using this word.

01:26:19.680 --> 01:26:23.070
We are going to dissect the
word, "heritability" big time

01:26:23.070 --> 01:26:25.830
in a short while--
There's about 70%

01:26:25.830 --> 01:26:31.440
heritability of political party
affiliation in this country.

01:26:31.440 --> 01:26:35.590
Sharing that behavioral
trait with your parents.

01:26:35.590 --> 01:26:36.660
Whoa.

01:26:36.660 --> 01:26:38.200
What is that about?

01:26:38.200 --> 01:26:40.190
That's sure disturbing.

01:26:40.190 --> 01:26:42.780
And that sure makes
you want to procreate

01:26:42.780 --> 01:26:45.890
in the name of your political
stances, or whatever.

01:26:45.890 --> 01:26:48.350
And this appears to
hold up pretty well

01:26:48.350 --> 01:26:51.310
to some of the standard
criticisms in the literature.

01:26:51.310 --> 01:26:53.340
And it's got nothing
to do with this.

01:26:53.340 --> 01:26:55.460
What's the mediating variable?

01:26:55.460 --> 01:26:58.030
A large really
interesting literature

01:26:58.030 --> 01:27:01.460
showing, when you compare
political or social

01:27:01.460 --> 01:27:05.610
progressives with political
or social conservatives, one

01:27:05.610 --> 01:27:08.280
of the most reliable
personality differences

01:27:08.280 --> 01:27:12.000
is how they feel
about ambiguity.

01:27:12.000 --> 01:27:16.220
Conservatives, on the average
do not like ambiguity.

01:27:16.220 --> 01:27:18.580
They are much more
ambiguity-averse.

01:27:18.580 --> 01:27:20.460
And you can start
it with showing

01:27:20.460 --> 01:27:23.470
ambiguous sensory
stimuli in kids

01:27:23.470 --> 01:27:26.170
and looking at heart
rate responses to it.

01:27:26.170 --> 01:27:29.470
And that tends to be a
stable personality difference

01:27:29.470 --> 01:27:31.460
at political extremes.

01:27:31.460 --> 01:27:33.940
You will see, some
time later on,

01:27:33.940 --> 01:27:37.060
that there's a whole world
of moral development in kids

01:27:37.060 --> 01:27:39.900
where there's various
scales measuring.

01:27:39.900 --> 01:27:42.910
One's Kohlberg's Stage
of Moral Development.

01:27:42.910 --> 01:27:44.760
There was an old
literature suggesting

01:27:44.760 --> 01:27:48.370
political differences as to
how fancy of a Kohlberg stage

01:27:48.370 --> 01:27:48.990
you got to.

01:27:48.990 --> 01:27:51.220
We will see that,
despite what struck me

01:27:51.220 --> 01:27:54.210
as the intuitive sort of
logic of what was found.

01:27:54.210 --> 01:27:55.440
That one hasn't held up.

01:27:55.440 --> 01:27:58.050
But one that does
hold up is difference

01:27:58.050 --> 01:28:00.210
in ambiguity tolerance.

01:28:00.210 --> 01:28:03.250
And that's probably
the mediating trait.

01:28:03.250 --> 01:28:07.340
It is not inheriting a tendency
to like elephants, or donkeys,

01:28:07.340 --> 01:28:08.140
or whatever.

01:28:08.140 --> 01:28:10.780
It is instead having
this intermediate trait.

01:28:10.780 --> 01:28:13.790
Final example of what would
be an intermediate trait.

01:28:13.790 --> 01:28:16.240
There's a whole bunch
of rat and mouse strains

01:28:16.240 --> 01:28:17.900
that have been
developed that have

01:28:17.900 --> 01:28:21.850
differing levels of aggression,
high aggression strains.

01:28:21.850 --> 01:28:23.810
And you do all the
proper controls,

01:28:23.810 --> 01:28:26.010
and you can show that
this is a genetic trait.

01:28:26.010 --> 01:28:28.630
Whoa, heritability
of aggression.

01:28:28.630 --> 01:28:32.600
We're suddenly back to twin
adoption studies and Kety

01:28:32.600 --> 01:28:35.360
with heritability of
criminality, all of that,

01:28:35.360 --> 01:28:38.720
heritability of aggression,
what's actually going on

01:28:38.720 --> 01:28:43.050
in all of the strains identified
to date by spontaneous traits

01:28:43.050 --> 01:28:44.800
coming up and then
breeding for it.

01:28:44.800 --> 01:28:47.040
What you see instead
is the strain

01:28:47.040 --> 01:28:51.330
that is so aggressive, and
so pissy, and so impossible,

01:28:51.330 --> 01:28:55.210
and so constrained by the law
and order of rodent society,

01:28:55.210 --> 01:28:56.070
and all of that.

01:28:56.070 --> 01:28:59.640
They've got a lower threshold
for pain sensitivity.

01:28:59.640 --> 01:29:01.860
Things hurt them more readily.

01:29:01.860 --> 01:29:04.080
And they're more likely
to become aggressive

01:29:04.080 --> 01:29:05.010
at that point.

01:29:05.010 --> 01:29:08.850
It turns out it's genetic
differences in the neurobiology

01:29:08.850 --> 01:29:10.530
of pain sensitivity.

01:29:10.530 --> 01:29:13.030
So what we're seeing
here, over and over is,

01:29:13.030 --> 01:29:16.410
amid the gazillion
of criticisms we've

01:29:16.410 --> 01:29:19.400
had about when does
environment actually start,

01:29:19.400 --> 01:29:21.200
and when do
environmental assumptions

01:29:21.200 --> 01:29:22.950
and being treated
the same go down

01:29:22.950 --> 01:29:25.630
the tubes, and differential
inheritance of genes,

01:29:25.630 --> 01:29:28.310
yeah some traits do appear
to have some fairly strong

01:29:28.310 --> 01:29:29.550
genetic components.

01:29:29.550 --> 01:29:32.940
But even once you get
that far, they very often

01:29:32.940 --> 01:29:36.230
are through some
very indirect routes.

01:29:36.230 --> 01:29:39.320
OK more things here.

01:29:39.320 --> 01:29:39.920
More things?

01:29:39.920 --> 01:29:41.100
We just covered that.

01:29:41.100 --> 01:29:43.430
OK, a little bit
more on epigenetics,

01:29:43.430 --> 01:29:44.830
which is that
whole business, you

01:29:44.830 --> 01:29:46.960
remember, from the
other day, which

01:29:46.960 --> 01:29:50.640
is after you've got
the DNA, and then you

01:29:50.640 --> 01:29:54.460
have that whole world of
protein coatings, which

01:29:54.460 --> 01:29:57.020
I've been very careful not
to give the jargony name for,

01:29:57.020 --> 01:29:58.326
because it's not important.

01:29:58.326 --> 01:29:59.950
But what you've got
is this whole world

01:29:59.950 --> 01:30:04.370
where regulation is not so
much at the level of genes--

01:30:04.370 --> 01:30:07.670
and in 95% of the DNA,
that's the on/off switches--

01:30:07.670 --> 01:30:11.210
but whether the transcription
factors can even get in there,

01:30:11.210 --> 01:30:14.160
and this world of
epigenetic changes

01:30:14.160 --> 01:30:17.030
that will cause lifelong
differences in how

01:30:17.030 --> 01:30:20.380
readily transcription factors
get to something or other.

01:30:20.380 --> 01:30:22.320
What have you got at that point?

01:30:22.320 --> 01:30:26.440
The exact same possibilities
as this one here.

01:30:26.440 --> 01:30:29.370
If instead of, due to
some environmental toxin,

01:30:29.370 --> 01:30:33.390
you knock a transcription factor
out of business in a fertilized

01:30:33.390 --> 01:30:36.830
egg where there's the set up
of genes, if for some reason,

01:30:36.830 --> 01:30:39.340
whatever, you do not
have access to it because

01:30:39.340 --> 01:30:41.140
of an epigenetic
change, it's going

01:30:41.140 --> 01:30:43.410
to be the exact
same consequence,

01:30:43.410 --> 01:30:47.460
multigenerational inheritance
of non-genetic traits

01:30:47.460 --> 01:30:51.240
due to epigenetic, rather
than genetic differences.

01:30:51.240 --> 01:30:54.630
That is turning out to be what
went on in the Dutch Hunger

01:30:54.630 --> 01:30:56.410
Winter people and
the animal models

01:30:56.410 --> 01:31:00.960
of epigenetic differences and
access of transcription factors

01:31:00.960 --> 01:31:03.770
to genes related to
insulin metabolism.

01:31:03.770 --> 01:31:06.120
That turns out to
be a critical one.

01:31:06.120 --> 01:31:09.140
Here is one of the coolest
examples of this to date.

01:31:09.140 --> 01:31:11.900
And this is work done by a guy
at McGill University, named

01:31:11.900 --> 01:31:13.440
Michael Meaney.

01:31:13.440 --> 01:31:17.930
And what he has focused
on is what started off

01:31:17.930 --> 01:31:20.840
as a very artificial
literature, which is,

01:31:20.840 --> 01:31:24.920
take yourself a newborn rat,
and for the first two weeks

01:31:24.920 --> 01:31:26.580
or so of its life,
every day, you

01:31:26.580 --> 01:31:29.730
pick it up for three
minutes and you pet it.

01:31:29.730 --> 01:31:31.210
And now, you put it back.

01:31:31.210 --> 01:31:33.130
And all else being
equal, it will

01:31:33.130 --> 01:31:36.220
have a bigger brain in
adulthood, better learning

01:31:36.220 --> 01:31:38.440
abilities, more resistance
to a whole bunch

01:31:38.440 --> 01:31:42.070
of neurological insults,
lower glucocorticoid levels,

01:31:42.070 --> 01:31:44.010
et cetera, that
whole world of what

01:31:44.010 --> 01:31:47.070
came to be known as
neonatal handling.

01:31:47.070 --> 01:31:49.120
On the other hand,
pick up the rat,

01:31:49.120 --> 01:31:51.720
take it away from mom
for, instead of 3 minutes,

01:31:51.720 --> 01:31:53.140
an hour and a half.

01:31:53.140 --> 01:31:55.190
Then each day, put him back.

01:31:55.190 --> 01:31:57.890
And as an adult, it's going
to have a smaller brain

01:31:57.890 --> 01:31:59.460
and a shorter life expectancy.

01:31:59.460 --> 01:32:01.950
Three minutes away
from mom does wonders.

01:32:01.950 --> 01:32:04.570
An hour and a half of
being petted does not.

01:32:04.570 --> 01:32:07.390
That, in and of itself,
is interesting in terms

01:32:07.390 --> 01:32:10.560
of what counts as stimulation,
what counts as stress.

01:32:10.560 --> 01:32:12.640
OK, so hurray.

01:32:12.640 --> 01:32:15.050
What we've just
learned is just how

01:32:15.050 --> 01:32:18.040
generations of rat-petting
graduate students

01:32:18.040 --> 01:32:22.140
can influence the lineages of
rat brains and all of that.

01:32:22.140 --> 01:32:25.750
And what Meanie started
looking at with this phenomenon

01:32:25.750 --> 01:32:28.380
being one that was around
forever-- first identified

01:32:28.380 --> 01:32:30.850
around 1960 by a
guy named Seymour

01:32:30.850 --> 01:32:32.930
Levine in the Psychiatry
Department here,

01:32:32.930 --> 01:32:35.350
and no longer alive-- but
that started this whole world

01:32:35.350 --> 01:32:36.620
of neonatal handling.

01:32:36.620 --> 01:32:39.710
What Meanie did
was say, well, rats

01:32:39.710 --> 01:32:41.580
did not evolve, whatever
is going on here,

01:32:41.580 --> 01:32:43.460
for the purpose of
doctoral theses,

01:32:43.460 --> 01:32:48.610
what's the natural equivalent
in the world of a rodent?

01:32:48.610 --> 01:32:51.580
And it turns out that what
happens when you pick up

01:32:51.580 --> 01:32:54.080
a rat for three minutes and
do this and put it back,

01:32:54.080 --> 01:32:57.590
mom is all excited and
goes and checks out the pup

01:32:57.590 --> 01:33:03.480
and nestles it, and licks it,
and whatever other stuff there.

01:33:03.480 --> 01:33:05.380
And it has all this attention.

01:33:05.380 --> 01:33:08.110
Whereas, if you take the pup
out for an hour and a half,

01:33:08.110 --> 01:33:10.970
when you put him back
with mom, mom basically

01:33:10.970 --> 01:33:13.840
ignores the pup for
long periods of time.

01:33:13.840 --> 01:33:16.600
You're changing the
mother's behavior.

01:33:16.600 --> 01:33:19.120
OK, so that's an
indirect effect.

01:33:19.120 --> 01:33:21.600
And what he
proceeded to show was

01:33:21.600 --> 01:33:24.110
the critical thing about
the handling was not

01:33:24.110 --> 01:33:26.210
what you're doing to the
rat during that time,

01:33:26.210 --> 01:33:27.810
it's the fact that
you're causing

01:33:27.810 --> 01:33:32.530
dramatic changes in maternal
behavior based on that.

01:33:32.530 --> 01:33:33.670
So that's interesting.

01:33:33.670 --> 01:33:35.420
But that still doesn't
solve the problem

01:33:35.420 --> 01:33:38.590
of why did the system
evolve for grad students

01:33:38.590 --> 01:33:40.690
manipulating maternal behavior.

01:33:40.690 --> 01:33:42.430
And what he then
proceeded to look at

01:33:42.430 --> 01:33:46.700
was normal variation in
rat mothering styles,

01:33:46.700 --> 01:33:49.900
because some rat
mothers are-- OK,

01:33:49.900 --> 01:33:52.210
I know this is a
value judgement--

01:33:52.210 --> 01:33:55.990
but some rat mothers are better
mothers than other mothers.

01:33:55.990 --> 01:33:59.965
Some rat mothers, they
simply are better.

01:33:59.965 --> 01:34:00.590
They're better.

01:34:00.590 --> 01:34:02.100
They're nicer they
have better souls.

01:34:02.100 --> 01:34:02.600
[LAUGHTER]

01:34:02.600 --> 01:34:05.230
And in these rat mothers,
how do you determine that

01:34:05.230 --> 01:34:06.600
by these sorts of measures?

01:34:06.600 --> 01:34:08.030
Licking and grooming.

01:34:08.030 --> 01:34:10.730
How much time do you
spend licking your baby?

01:34:10.730 --> 01:34:13.230
And how much time do you
spend grooming your baby?

01:34:13.230 --> 01:34:15.040
And what Meanie
proceeded to show

01:34:15.040 --> 01:34:19.080
is that's what the neonatal
handling phenomenon was about.

01:34:19.080 --> 01:34:23.500
When you have moms who lick and
groom their kids an awful lot,

01:34:23.500 --> 01:34:27.110
what you do is produce the
same sort of better outcome.

01:34:27.110 --> 01:34:29.690
From the three minutes
of petting deal there,

01:34:29.690 --> 01:34:32.740
you get the kid who is
bigger, and healthier,

01:34:32.740 --> 01:34:34.240
and smarter, that sort of thing.

01:34:34.240 --> 01:34:37.090
Moms who hardly ever lick
and groom their pups,

01:34:37.090 --> 01:34:38.950
they produce pups
that, as adults,

01:34:38.950 --> 01:34:40.500
are like the ones
that were separated

01:34:40.500 --> 01:34:42.200
for an hour and a half a day.

01:34:42.200 --> 01:34:45.580
It is a reflection
of mothering style

01:34:45.580 --> 01:34:48.890
in the rats and the
variability there.

01:34:48.890 --> 01:34:53.920
Next thing he showed was that
this was multigenerational.

01:34:53.920 --> 01:34:58.700
If you lick and groom your
baby rat daughter a whole lot,

01:34:58.700 --> 01:35:02.740
as an adult, she will be
more of a licker and groomer.

01:35:02.740 --> 01:35:05.920
And he's already shown what some
of the neurological mechanisms

01:35:05.920 --> 01:35:06.655
are for that.

01:35:06.655 --> 01:35:08.570
For development,
what have we got?

01:35:08.570 --> 01:35:12.600
Yet again, one of these
non-Mendelian inheritance

01:35:12.600 --> 01:35:14.700
of traits deals going on.

01:35:14.700 --> 01:35:16.790
In this case, not even prenatal.

01:35:16.790 --> 01:35:20.780
Your early experience is going
to cause lifelong changes

01:35:20.780 --> 01:35:22.700
in your brain, which
will make you more

01:35:22.700 --> 01:35:25.610
likely to reproduce the
same early experience

01:35:25.610 --> 01:35:26.650
for your offspring.

01:35:26.650 --> 01:35:27.900
Off you go.

01:35:27.900 --> 01:35:30.030
The final thing he
did, which stands

01:35:30.030 --> 01:35:33.360
as a landmark in the field
of behavioral neurobiology,

01:35:33.360 --> 01:35:37.420
is he figured out what
the epigenetic change is.

01:35:37.420 --> 01:35:39.710
One of them, or
rather two of them

01:35:39.710 --> 01:35:42.980
is identified by now,
what gets changed

01:35:42.980 --> 01:35:46.670
by how mom often or
un-often licks you,

01:35:46.670 --> 01:35:48.150
grooms you, all of that?

01:35:48.150 --> 01:35:51.520
You change the access
of transcription factors

01:35:51.520 --> 01:35:57.420
relevant to activating
genes for making receptors

01:35:57.420 --> 01:36:02.350
for stress hormones, making
receptors for estrogen,

01:36:02.350 --> 01:36:05.570
making receptors for a whole
bunch of different hormones.

01:36:05.570 --> 01:36:08.240
Showing the epigenetic
changes there,

01:36:08.240 --> 01:36:12.340
that's how you go from moms
differing maternal style

01:36:12.340 --> 01:36:15.170
to lifelong differences
in expression

01:36:15.170 --> 01:36:17.840
of all sorts of genes.

01:36:17.840 --> 01:36:19.060
How's this?

01:36:19.060 --> 01:36:23.050
What you wind up seeing there
as this permanent mechanism,

01:36:23.050 --> 01:36:26.350
it is also reversible,
what he has since shown,

01:36:26.350 --> 01:36:28.570
which is you have a
baby rat who spends

01:36:28.570 --> 01:36:31.500
the first half of its
infancy with some totally

01:36:31.500 --> 01:36:35.446
terrible, negligent, distracted
mom who pays no attention

01:36:35.446 --> 01:36:36.570
and doesn't do any licking.

01:36:36.570 --> 01:36:41.110
Now cross-foster the pup
to a more attentive mother,

01:36:41.110 --> 01:36:44.380
and you can change the
epigenetic pattern.

01:36:44.380 --> 01:36:47.560
So all of this has
two themes going on.

01:36:47.560 --> 01:36:51.510
Early experience, causing
really persistent differences

01:36:51.510 --> 01:36:53.770
in how this stuff
works long after,

01:36:53.770 --> 01:36:57.630
and experience later on having
the potential to reverse

01:36:57.630 --> 01:36:58.320
some of this.

01:36:58.320 --> 01:37:02.520
All of this stuff, once again,
would be mistaken for genetic.

01:37:02.520 --> 01:37:04.590
What we have here
is what appears

01:37:04.590 --> 01:37:08.960
to be a genetic style of what
sort of mother rat you are.

01:37:08.960 --> 01:37:12.140
And it's not genes,
it's the mothering style

01:37:12.140 --> 01:37:15.860
setting up the offspring for
being a similar type of mother.

01:37:15.860 --> 01:37:18.910
Incredibly important
studies demonstrating this.

01:37:18.910 --> 01:37:21.460
What remains unclear
is how you get

01:37:21.460 --> 01:37:24.980
from mom licking you to
something epigenetic happening

01:37:24.980 --> 01:37:25.610
here.

01:37:25.610 --> 01:37:27.720
His crew is pounding
away at that.

01:37:27.720 --> 01:37:29.370
OK, so what have we
got at this point?

01:37:29.370 --> 01:37:31.680
We have gone through
over and over here--

01:37:31.680 --> 01:37:33.460
where have we gotten
to at this point?

01:37:33.460 --> 01:37:37.770
We've gone over and over here at
all of the classical techniques

01:37:37.770 --> 01:37:39.760
in the field of
behavior genetics,

01:37:39.760 --> 01:37:43.180
does it run in families,
adoptive studies,

01:37:43.180 --> 01:37:46.020
identical versus
monozygotic twins,

01:37:46.020 --> 01:37:47.190
twins separated at birth.

01:37:47.190 --> 01:37:49.090
We saw all of the
problems with it.

01:37:49.090 --> 01:37:52.130
And most dramatically,
most excitingly these days,

01:37:52.130 --> 01:37:54.130
prenatal environmental effects.

01:37:54.130 --> 01:37:57.940
We saw that trying to separate
maternal prenatal effects

01:37:57.940 --> 01:38:00.120
from paternal
genetic effects hits

01:38:00.120 --> 01:38:03.020
a wall, when you get all
of these weird-o hereditary

01:38:03.020 --> 01:38:06.910
things, including potentially
non-genetic Lamarckian

01:38:06.910 --> 01:38:08.380
inheritance of a trait.

01:38:08.380 --> 01:38:12.130
And what we've seen is how this
stuff playing out early in life

01:38:12.130 --> 01:38:14.560
has multigenerational
consequences.

01:38:14.560 --> 01:38:16.920
What we're going to pick
up with on Wednesday

01:38:16.920 --> 01:38:19.790
is now looking at how
people in this business

01:38:19.790 --> 01:38:24.140
find the actual genes, and
ultimately, gene environment

01:38:24.140 --> 01:38:28.630
interactions that make the last
two hours basically irrelevant.

01:38:28.630 --> 01:38:30.490
OK.

01:38:30.490 --> 01:38:33.760
For more, please visit
us at stanford.edu.

